Around line 4573 of AbstractTextEditor towards the end of the metod createNavigationActions, there's a line towards the end of  the method createNavigationActions which inexplicably disables the delete key.  Backspace, etc, still work as expected.  I quote:-

// to accommodate https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=51516
// nullify handling of DELETE key by StyledText
textWidget.setKeyBinding(SWT.DEL, SWT.NULL);

Bug 51516 has been marked fixed and I can only presume that this code should have been deleted or never committed in the first place.

I encountered this problem with our RCP app using a source viewer.  It took me forever to find out why it wasn't working...

I had to work around this by overriding this method and reinstating the delete key binding like this:-

StyledText textWidget = getSourceViewer().getTextWidget();
super.createNavigationActions();
textWidget.setKeyBinding(SWT.DEL, ST.DELETE_NEXT);

The Delete key works for me using these simple steps:
1. create this class in my.editors package: public class MyEditor extends AbstractDecoratedTextEditor {
}
2. register above editor in plugin.xml <editor id="my.editors.MyEditor" name="%FromAbstractDecoratedTextEditor.name" icon="file_obj.gif" class="my.editors.FromAbstractDecoratedTextEditor"> <contentTypeBinding contentTypeId="org.eclipse.core.runtime.text" /> </editor>
Start target ==> Delete key works (tested on Linux-GTK).
It also works if AbstractTextEditor is used as super class and a document provider is set in the constructor, e.g. public MyEditor() { setDocumentProvider(new TextFileDocumentProvider()); }

